73
00:04:23,333 --> 00:04:27,243
In the past, we have modeled access
control or permissions in different ways.

74
00:04:27,653 --> 00:04:29,313
We started with access lists.

75
00:04:30,173 --> 00:04:32,753
Say you have a document called Document 1.

76
00:04:33,113 --> 00:04:36,143
You have a list of all people
who can edit this document.

77
00:04:37,113 --> 00:04:40,283
S- now you also have to have a
separate list of all people who

78
00:04:40,283 --> 00:04:42,643
can write or read this document.

79
00:04:43,063 --> 00:04:44,743
What about people who can comment?

80
00:04:44,903 --> 00:04:48,923
That's a new list, and not very
scalable That changed in the

81
00:04:48,923 --> 00:04:53,023
industry to something called roles
or role-based access control or RBAC.

82
00:04:53,533 --> 00:04:56,853
And this is very popular, and
I'm sure you've used it at your

83
00:04:56,853 --> 00:05:00,833
workplace as well, where everyone's
assigned a role, and based on that

84
00:05:00,833 --> 00:05:02,723
role, you get a set of permissions.

85
00:05:03,133 --> 00:05:06,493
So for instance if you are a software
engineer, you can check in code

86
00:05:06,493 --> 00:05:08,063
or you can read code repositories.

87
00:05:08,673 --> 00:05:11,423
If you're in sales, you can
read sales reports, et cetera.

88
00:05:12,183 --> 00:05:14,873
Now, this is simple and works
until it doesn't, because

89
00:05:14,903 --> 00:05:16,173
this again does not scale.

90
00:05:16,593 --> 00:05:20,183
What if someone from the software
engineering team has to check a sales

91
00:05:20,183 --> 00:05:22,453
report for something to do with code?

92
00:05:23,053 --> 00:05:26,893
You have to create a new role and
more and more, and suddenly you have

93
00:05:26,893 --> 00:05:30,803
a role explosion that you can't audit
that can lead to security issues.

94
00:05:31,193 --> 00:05:35,953
And the minute something changes, you need
a new role or an old role becomes stale.

95
00:05:36,453 --> 00:05:40,193
There's also attribute-based access
control where you have rules and

96
00:05:40,203 --> 00:05:42,193
things are broken down into attributes.

97
00:05:42,593 --> 00:05:46,453
So if I'm trying to access a file, it
looks like, it looks at my attributes

98
00:05:46,473 --> 00:05:52,263
like name email ID, location, department,
workspace, and based on all of these

99
00:05:52,263 --> 00:05:53,963
attributes, I get a yes or a no.

100
00:05:54,813 --> 00:05:59,073
Again, this again works till it
doesn't 'cause it is very rule-heavy,

101
00:05:59,093 --> 00:06:04,213
and it can be hard to audit at scale,
especially if you're using AI agents.

102
00:06:04,713 --> 00:06:08,993
The sort of new kid on the block
is something called ReBAC or

103
00:06:08,993 --> 00:06:14,703
relationship-based access control, where
the idea is you can express relationships

104
00:06:14,723 --> 00:06:17,063
between different things in your system.

105
00:06:17,533 --> 00:06:20,813
So for instance, there's a user
and a resource, like a document,

106
00:06:20,883 --> 00:06:22,523
there's a relationship between them.

107
00:06:23,193 --> 00:06:28,563
And this seems to be the predominant
model right now in, in enterprise

108
00:06:28,603 --> 00:06:30,933
and in the world of AI as well.

109
00:06:31,273 --> 00:06:34,443
And in the next few slides,
I will tell you why that is.

110
00:06:35,403 --> 00:06:37,253
Before that, a little
bit of a history lesson.

111
00:06:37,873 --> 00:06:41,393
ReBAC was actually popularized in
something called Google Zanzibar.

112
00:06:41,893 --> 00:06:42,883
See the word mentioned there.

113
00:06:43,223 --> 00:06:47,863
Now, in 2019, Google released this
white paper called Google Zanzibar,

114
00:06:48,263 --> 00:06:52,003
and in it they described their
internal authorization system,

115
00:06:52,013 --> 00:06:53,823
also called Google Zanzibar.

116
00:06:54,323 --> 00:06:58,883
And this was a groundbreak- groundbreaking
paper because for the first time a

117
00:06:58,883 --> 00:07:03,223
company at the scale of Google, we're
talking billions of objects, hundreds

118
00:07:03,223 --> 00:07:08,203
of millions of users in every part
of the world, describe in detail how

119
00:07:08,223 --> 00:07:10,193
their authorization model worked.

120
00:07:11,143 --> 00:07:17,403
The idea is it was globally distributed
and even back in 2019, the system could

121
00:07:17,493 --> 00:07:20,433
do more than 10 million checks per second.

122
00:07:20,883 --> 00:07:24,563
I am so sure that number has
exponentially increased by now.

123
00:07:25,063 --> 00:07:29,373
If you have used any Google product like
Docs, YouTube, Maps, Photos, whatever,

124
00:07:30,043 --> 00:07:33,863
this is the system that actually is doing
the authorization behind the scenes.

125
00:07:34,063 --> 00:07:37,823
So if you have ever clicked on
a Google Docs link and you've

126
00:07:37,823 --> 00:07:41,303
seen access denied that is the
Google Zanzibar system working.

127
00:07:41,803 --> 00:07:44,513
And the cool thing is, at Google,
if you're just a developer

128
00:07:44,743 --> 00:07:46,413
it's just an API then, right?

129
00:07:46,453 --> 00:07:48,133
You don't have to worry
about how it works.

130
00:07:48,853 --> 00:07:53,333
You call an API which answers a
simple question: Is an actor allowed

131
00:07:53,333 --> 00:07:56,163
to perform an action on a resource?

132
00:07:56,483 --> 00:07:58,043
For example, me, Sohan.

133
00:07:58,273 --> 00:08:00,443
Is Sohan allowed to edit document one?

134
00:08:00,943 --> 00:08:02,543
And you get a yes or a no.

135
00:08:03,243 --> 00:08:05,623
And in effect, you're basically
checking for permission.

136
00:08:05,753 --> 00:08:07,393
This is authorization.

137
00:08:07,893 --> 00:08:11,813
Let's dive a little bit deep into
this ReBAC, because it's key to

138
00:08:11,813 --> 00:08:17,893
understanding how you can use that to add
authorization for AI and coding agents.

139
00:08:18,393 --> 00:08:22,283
Essentially, in ReBAC, you
have an actor and a resource.

140
00:08:22,293 --> 00:08:25,623
So in this case, say a user…
I'm gonna get my mouse here.

141
00:08:25,813 --> 00:08:30,253
A user and an object or a resource,
which could be a doc, it could be a

142
00:08:30,253 --> 00:08:32,803
folder, a code repository, map, whatever.

143
00:08:33,303 --> 00:08:37,643
There has to exist a relationship
between the user and that object, and

144
00:08:37,643 --> 00:08:43,003
that relation could be something like
user is a member of a group, or user

145
00:08:43,043 --> 00:08:49,773
is an editor of a document, or user
is an owner of folder named Plans.

146
00:08:50,313 --> 00:08:54,523
So object-resource
relationship between the two.

147
00:08:55,023 --> 00:09:00,843
Once you have this, you basically tell
the system that this relationship exists

148
00:09:00,883 --> 00:09:02,823
in the form of something called a tuple.

149
00:09:03,613 --> 00:09:09,563
This is the format of a tuple Start at
the right, and in this you would say user

150
00:09:09,563 --> 00:09:12,513
number three is the owner of document 123.

151
00:09:13,253 --> 00:09:18,383
So say you've created a new link or
a new Google Doc file, something like

152
00:09:18,383 --> 00:09:22,083
this has actually been written in
the backend system where it says user

153
00:09:22,493 --> 00:09:25,533
345 is the owner of document 12345.

154
00:09:26,033 --> 00:09:31,383
And this is how a system knows that
this relationship exists So after

155
00:09:31,383 --> 00:09:35,063
the creation of all these tuples,
what are we doing with this data?

156
00:09:35,383 --> 00:09:40,333
This is where it gets interesting because
the Zanzibar system basically, or any RBAC

157
00:09:40,333 --> 00:09:45,643
system, essentially constructs a graph
from all of this relationship data, and

158
00:09:45,643 --> 00:09:47,483
the graph would look something like this.

159
00:09:47,983 --> 00:09:52,133
The idea is once you have a lot
of relations between objects

160
00:09:52,153 --> 00:09:56,023
and resources, you can construct
something called a directed

161
00:09:56,403 --> 00:09:58,283
acyclic graph or a directed graph.

162
00:09:58,923 --> 00:10:05,153
And to check permissions, you have to
just check if there's a way to go from the

163
00:10:05,163 --> 00:10:07,683
object to the resource via the permission.

164
00:10:08,643 --> 00:10:12,643
In the graph, you will see that each edge
or each node in the graph is either the

165
00:10:12,643 --> 00:10:14,633
object, the resource, or the permission.

166
00:10:14,683 --> 00:10:18,553
Say you have some document, and
you have readers, Fred and Kim.

167
00:10:19,343 --> 00:10:21,873
You have writers that are Jill and Niv.

168
00:10:22,593 --> 00:10:26,433
And say you have an organization
called Acme with an admin, Niv.

169
00:10:26,933 --> 00:10:29,843
Here are the key things, which is
the little dotted line that you

170
00:10:29,843 --> 00:10:32,133
see between reader and writer.

171
00:10:32,633 --> 00:10:36,643
Now, this indicates if you can write to
the file, you can also read the file.

172
00:10:37,143 --> 00:10:40,623
This little dotted line here from
writer to admin indicates that if you're

173
00:10:40,623 --> 00:10:42,623
a admin, you can write to the file.

174
00:10:43,333 --> 00:10:47,353
And we know that if you can write to
the file, you can already read the file.

175
00:10:47,853 --> 00:10:49,123
So say a check comes in.

176
00:10:49,633 --> 00:10:52,073
Can Jill read some document?

177
00:10:52,573 --> 00:10:57,263
I want you to take a look at this
diagram and tell me if there is

178
00:10:57,593 --> 00:11:02,963
a unidirectional way to go from
some document to Jill via reader

179
00:11:03,463 --> 00:11:07,733
Now, the answer, of course, is on the
screen, but the answer is yes, because

180
00:11:07,753 --> 00:11:13,743
you can go from some document to reader
to writer to Jill, and hence Jill

181
00:11:13,763 --> 00:11:16,423
has permission to read some document.

182
00:11:16,923 --> 00:11:17,873
Here's another question.

183
00:11:18,233 --> 00:11:20,923
Can Fred write to this document?

184
00:11:21,423 --> 00:11:26,723
If you see, there's no unidirectional
way to go from some document to writer

185
00:11:26,833 --> 00:11:32,373
to Fred, and hence Fred does not have
permissions to write to the document.

186
00:11:32,863 --> 00:11:38,933
Essentially, this is a graph reachability
problem, and that's what ReBAC is, and

187
00:11:38,933 --> 00:11:41,003
this is how ReBAC works behind the scenes.

188
00:11:41,303 --> 00:11:46,323
You d- you draw all of these relationships
between the different objects in your

189
00:11:46,323 --> 00:11:50,513
system, your users, your agents, your
documents, your code, and then when you

190
00:11:50,513 --> 00:11:55,183
check for permission, you can traverse
this graph and check for permission.

191
00:11:55,793 --> 00:12:00,423
And this is useful because in the
world of role-based access control

192
00:12:00,923 --> 00:12:05,273
You can't actually say a path or a
command or a domain, for instance.

193
00:12:05,543 --> 00:12:08,003
You will just give a role
like a developer, which what

194
00:12:08,003 --> 00:12:09,743
we call very coarse-grained.

195
00:12:09,993 --> 00:12:12,323
It's not fine-grained, it's
coarse, it's very broad.

196
00:12:12,823 --> 00:12:16,343
So a developer accesses
all the code or nothing.

197
00:12:16,453 --> 00:12:20,473
It's not the developer can access just
the code that they are working on.

198
00:12:21,423 --> 00:12:25,623
And again, this is important in the
world of AI agents because what a coding

199
00:12:25,623 --> 00:12:32,253
agent need is something like write only
to your SRC file or run only Go test

200
00:12:32,283 --> 00:12:35,093
or fetch data only from github.com.

201
00:12:35,743 --> 00:12:40,543
These are the things that keep your
data safe when using a coding assistant

202
00:12:41,043 --> 00:12:44,503
Zanzibar, of course, is an internal
Google tool, so you and I can't use

203
00:12:44,543 --> 00:12:46,263
it unless you're working for Google.

204
00:12:46,763 --> 00:12:52,543
So how do you use a Zanzibar
model to actually do RBAC style

205
00:12:52,683 --> 00:12:55,323
fine-grained permissions for your
app or for your coding agents?

206
00:12:56,263 --> 00:13:01,293
About five years ago, there was a popular
open source now popular open source

207
00:13:01,773 --> 00:13:06,653
piece of software called SpiceDB that
was an implementation of Google Zanzibar.

208
00:13:07,513 --> 00:13:11,573
SpiceDB, which is something that
I work on, is an open source

209
00:13:11,633 --> 00:13:14,993
implementation which tries to be
as faithful to Google Zanzibar.

210
00:13:15,493 --> 00:13:19,433
Essentially, as the name suggests,
it's a highly parallel graph database

211
00:13:19,893 --> 00:13:22,273
optimized only for authorization queries.

212
00:13:23,033 --> 00:13:27,733
And for you and me as devs, think
of it as a gRPC or HTTP API.

213
00:13:28,073 --> 00:13:28,713
It's written in Go.

214
00:13:29,563 --> 00:13:33,133
And SpiceDB answers questions
such as, "Can a subject take

215
00:13:33,193 --> 00:13:36,333
an action on a resource?" The
thing that I just spoke about.

216
00:13:37,073 --> 00:13:41,233
You'd be surprised to know that
SpiceDB is very popular, about

217
00:13:41,273 --> 00:13:42,823
close to 7,000 stars on GitHub.

218
00:13:43,272 --> 00:13:46,593
It's also used in enterprises
such as OpenAI, Zoom.

219
00:13:47,153 --> 00:13:50,893
It, it has contributions from
companies like Netflix, Google,

220
00:13:50,993 --> 00:13:53,273
GitHub, et cetera, on its features.

221
00:13:53,313 --> 00:13:56,663
And in my opinion, it's becoming
like an industry standard when

222
00:13:56,673 --> 00:14:00,273
